Supervised Learning Classification Project: AllLife Bank Personal Loan Campaign

Problem Statement

Context

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data scientist at AllLife bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customers age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)? (0: No, 1: Yes)

# function to create histogram and boxplot
def plot_histogram_boxplot(data: df, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Create a combined boxplot and histogram for a specified feature.

    Parameters:
    - data: DataFrame
    - feature: str, column name in the DataFrame
    - figsize: tuple, size of the figure (default (12, 7))
    - kde: bool, whether to show the density curve (default False)
    - bins: int, number of bins for the histogram (default None)
    """
    # Create subplots with shared x-axis
    fig, (ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=figsize, gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": [0.25, 0.75]})

    # Create a boxplot with means
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box, showmeans=True, color="violet")

    # Create a histogram with or without a kernel density estimate (KDE)
    hist_kws = {"kde": kde} if not bins else {"kde": kde, "bins": bins, "palette": "winter"}
    sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_hist, **hist_kws)

    # Add mean and median lines to the histogram
    for val, color, linestyle, label in [(data[feature].mean(), "green", "--", "Mean"), (data[feature].median(), "black", "-", "Median")]:
        ax_hist.axvline(val, color=color, linestyle=linestyle, label=label)

    # Set plot labels and legend
    ax_hist.set_xlabel(feature)
    ax_hist.set_ylabel("Frequency")
    ax_hist.legend()

    # Show the plot
    plt.show()

# function to create labeled barplots
def create_labeled_barplot(
    data: df,
    feature: str,
    display_percentages: bool=False,
    top_n: int=None
):
    """
    Create a barplot for a feature with labels on top.

    Parameters:
    - data: DataFrame containing the data
    - feature: String, name of the feature column in the DataFrame
    - display_percentages: Bool, if True, display percentages, else display counts (default is False)
    - top_n: Int or None, if int, display top n categories, else display all (default is None)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])
    count_unique = data[feature].nunique()

    # Determine plot size
    if top_n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count_unique + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(top_n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)

    # Create the countplot
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:top_n].sort_values(),
    )

    # Add labels on top of the bars
    for p in ax.patches:
        label = (
            f"{100 * p.get_height() / total:.1f}%" if display_percentages
            else f"{p.get_height()}"
        )

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2
        y = p.get_height()

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center", va="center",
            size=12, xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points"
        )

    plt.show()

def plot_stacked_bar(data: pd.DataFrame, predictor: str, target: str):
    """
    Display category counts and create a stacked bar chart.

    Parameters:
    - data: DataFrame containing the relevant data.
    - predictor: String, column name to be used as the independent variable in the plot.
    - target: String, column name to be used as the target variable in the plot.
    """
    count_unique = data[predictor].nunique()

    # Sorting criteria based on the last index of target variable value counts
    sorting_criteria = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]

    # Crosstab with all values including margins
    crosstab_with_margins = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True)\
                               .sort_values(by=sorting_criteria, ascending=False)

    print(crosstab_with_margins)
    print("-" * 120)

    # Normalized crosstab for percentage stacked bar plot
    normalized_crosstab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index")\
                             .sort_values(by=sorting_criteria, ascending=False)

    # Creating the plot
    normalized_crosstab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count_unique + 5, 5))

    plt.legend(loc="lower left", frameon=False)
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

### function to plot distributions wrt target

def plot_distributions_and_boxplots(data: pd.DataFrame, predictor: str, target: str):
    """
    Plot distributions and boxplots of a predictor variable with respect to a binary target variable.

    Parameters:
    - data: pd.DataFrame containing the relevant data.
    - predictor: str, column name to be used on the x-axis in the plots.
    - target: str, binary column name to be used to differentiate distributions.
    """
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))
    unique_targets = data[target].unique()

    # Plotting distributions for each unique target value
    for i, uniq in enumerate(unique_targets):
        axs[0, i].set_title(f"Distribution of {predictor} for {target}={uniq}")
        sns.histplot(
            data=data[data[target] == uniq],
            x=predictor,
            kde=True,
            ax=axs[0, i],
            color="teal" if i == 0 else "orange",
            stat="density",
        )

    # Plotting boxplots with respect to the target
    axs[1, 0].set_title(f"Boxplot of {predictor} w.r.t {target}")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title(f"Boxplot of {predictor} (without outliers) w.r.t {target}")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Observations:

  • Income and CCAvg: There is a strong positive correlation (0.65), indicating that as one's income increases, the average spending on credit cards also tends to increase.

  • Income and Personal_Loan: A positive correlation (0.50) suggests that higher-income customers are more likely to accept a personal loan.

  • CCAvg and Personal_Loan: A fairly strong positive correlation (0.37) indicates that customers who spend more on credit cards per month are more likely to accept a personal loan.

  • Personal_Loan and CD_Account: There's a positive correlation (0.32), indicating that customers who accepted the personal loan are also more likely to have a certificate of deposit account with the bank.

  • Securities_Account and CD_Account: A positive correlation (0.32) suggests a tendency that customers who have a securities account are also more likely to have a CD account.

  • Income and Mortgage: A positive correlation (0.21) shows that higher-income customers tend to have higher mortgage values.

  • Age and Experience: A very strong positive correlation (0.99), which is expected since more aged individuals tend to have more work experience.

  • Educational purposes: Negative correlations with Income and CCAvg (-0.19 and -0.14 respectively) suggest that higher educational levels do not necessarily correspond to higher incomes or credit card spending in this dataset.

  • Online and CD_Account: There is a modest positive correlation (0.18) between online banking usage and having a CD account. This suggests that customers who utilize online banking facilities are somewhat more likely to have a Certificate of Deposit (CD) account with the bank.

Outlier Detection

In [48]:
Q1 = df.quantile(0.25, numeric_only=True)  # Calculate the 25th percentile
Q3 = df.quantile(0.75, numeric_only=True) # Calculate the 75th percentile

IQR = Q3 - Q1  # Interquartile Range (75th percentile - 25th percentile)

# Calculating lower and upper bounds for all values.
# Any value outside these bounds may be considered an outlier.
lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
In [51]:
numeric_columns = df.select_dtypes(include=["float64", "int64"])
percentage_outliers = (

)

Model Building

In [57]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [58]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

However, it's important to exercise caution and consider potential limitations. The true test of a model's capability lies in its performance on unseen or test data. Achieving perfection on the training data can sometimes be a sign of overfitting, where the model memorizes the training set but struggles to generalize to new, unseen examples. To assess its robustness and practical utility, the model should undergo evaluation on a separate test dataset to ensure its ability to perform well in real-world scenarios.

Pre-Pruning

In [69]:
# Choose the type of classifier.
estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight="balanced", random_state=1)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {
    "max_depth": np.arange(5, 10),
    "criterion": ["entropy", "gini"],
    "splitter": ["best"],
    "min_impurity_decrease": [0.00001, 0.0001, 0.1]
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
acc_scorer = make_scorer(recall_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(estimator, parameters, scoring=acc_scorer, cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
estimator = grid_obj.best_estimator_

estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations

  • What recommedations would you suggest to the bank?

Below is the Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations:

  • Target High-Income Customers: Focus marketing efforts on customers with higher incomes, as they are more likely to accept personal loans. Tailor loan products or offers to appeal to this segment.

  • Leverage Credit Card Spending: Encourage credit card usage among customers, as there is a positive correlation between higher credit card spending and personal loan acceptance. Promote credit card features that align with customers' spending habits.

  • Family Size Matters: Recognize that customers from families with 3 or 4 members have higher acceptance rates for personal loans. Design loan packages that cater to the financial needs of larger families.

  • Education-Targeted Marketing: Craft marketing campaigns that resonate with customers of different education levels. Customers with advanced/professional education levels are more likely to accept personal loans; therefore, address their specific financial needs.

  • Online Banking Promotion: Promote online banking services to the remaining 40% of customers who do not utilize them. Offer incentives or discounts for online banking users to increase adoption rates.

  • ZIP Code-Based Strategies: Investigate the reasons behind varying acceptance rates in different ZIP codes. Implement localized marketing strategies or personalized offers to improve loan acceptance in areas with lower rates.

  • Outlier Investigation: Investigate potential outliers in columns like "Income," "CCAvg," and "Mortgage" to understand their nature and whether they represent valid data points. Outliers can impact model performance and analysis results.

  • Customer Segmentation: Segment customers based on income, family size, education, and online banking usage to create targeted marketing campaigns. Tailor loan products to suit the financial profiles of each segment.

  • Customer Education: Educate customers about the benefits and features of securities accounts and Certificate of Deposit (CD) accounts. Highlight the advantages of these services to increase adoption rates.

  • Continuous Model Monitoring: Continue monitoring the performance of the decision tree model, especially regarding precision and recall. Adjust marketing strategies based on model insights.

  • Customer Feedback: Gather feedback from customers who accepted personal loans to understand their motivations and needs. Use this information to refine loan offerings.

  • Competitive Analysis: Analyze competitors' offerings and strategies in the market. Differentiate your loan products and services to attract a larger share of the target audience.

By implementing these actionable insights and recommendations, the bank can improve its personal loan acceptance rates, enhance customer satisfaction, and optimize its marketing efforts.
